{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KWyQ6Awve88pGTrfXjsrGv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the types, `ListItemButton` uses `ExtendButtonBase` and `OverrideProps`. This is the standard MUI polymorphic component pattern. Let me check what `ExtendButtonBase` looks like.\n\nActually, let me just go with a simple and reliable approach. Since MUI's `ListItemButton` has an `href` property via the button base, I can just pass `href` directly and it will render as an `<a>` tag internally:\n\n```tsx\n<ListItemButton href={href} selected={pathname === href}>\n```\n\nWait, but does `ListItemButton` accept `href`? It should since it extends `ButtonBase` which extends HTML button attributes. \n\nBut that won't give me Next.js client-side navigation. The cleanest solution is wrapping `ListItemButton` with Next's `Link` component using `passHref` and `legacyBehavior`, then setting the component to render as an anchor tag so MUI handles the styling properly.\n\nActually, in Next.js 13+, I don't need `legacyBehavior` or `passHref` anymore—I can just pass `Link` as the component directly to `ListItemButton` with the `href` prop. The issue is that TypeScript complains because `ListItemButton` doesn't recognize `href` as a valid prop.\n\nLet me try using `component={NextLink}` and add a type assertion or biome ignore comment if TypeScript still complains. This is a standard MUI pattern, so it should work fine.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2409,"cache_read_input_tokens":48537,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2409},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7403e36d-f38b-4e9e-9fc7-7da8aea5eeed","uuid":"b86fabb2-ee12-4cce-8232-c8cb5ba85ed5"}
